        <h1>Vedas & Upanishads - The Essence of Vedic Wisdom</h1>
        
        <h2>The Four Vedas</h2>
        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/rig-veda.jpg" alt="Rig Veda">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Rig Veda</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Rig Veda</span> is the oldest and most revered Vedic text, consisting of hymns praising the deities. It serves as the foundation of Hindu philosophy, rituals, and cosmology.</p>
                <p>It is composed of over 1,000 hymns, arranged into ten books called Mandalas. These hymns explore the divine forces of nature, cosmic order, and moral duties.</p>
                <p>The Rig Veda also lays the groundwork for early Hindu thought, including concepts of dharma (righteousness) and rta (cosmic order), which continue to influence Hindu traditions today.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
       
        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/yajur-eda.jpeg" alt="Yajur Veda">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Yajur Veda</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Yajur Veda</span> is known as the book of sacrificial rituals. It provides instructions for various Yajnas (sacrificial ceremonies) and rituals that ensure cosmic harmony.</p>
                <p>It consists of prose and verse formulas that priests chant during rituals, linking the human and divine realms.</p>
                <p>The Yajur Veda is divided into two main parts: the Krishna (black) Yajur Veda and the Shukla (white) Yajur Veda, each with its interpretations and methodologies.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/sam-veda.jpeg" alt="Sama Veda">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Sama Veda</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Sama Veda</span> is the Veda of melodies and chants, serving as the foundation for Indian classical music and Vedic recitation.</p>
                <p>It consists of hymns primarily derived from the Rig Veda, but arranged musically to be sung during rituals.</p>
                <p>The Sama Veda plays a crucial role in spiritual devotion, emphasizing the power of sound and vibrations in connecting with the divine.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/atharva-veda.jpeg" alt="Atharva Veda">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Atharva Veda</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Atharva Veda</span> is distinct from the other Vedas, focusing on practical knowledge, healing, and everyday life.</p>
                <p>It contains hymns related to medicine, magic, charms, and protection from evil forces, highlighting the holistic nature of Vedic wisdom.</p>
                <p>The Atharva Veda provides insights into early Indian medicine, ethics, and social philosophy, influencing later Ayurvedic traditions.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <h2>The Major Upanishads</h2>
        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/isha-upanishad.jpeg" alt="Isha Upanishad">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Isha Upanishad</h3>
                <p>This Upanishad emphasizes the presence of the divine in all things and encourages a life of detachment while remaining engaged in the world.</p>
                <p>It teaches that true renunciation does not mean abandoning life but rather understanding the impermanence of material possessions.</p>
                <p>The Isha Upanishadâ€™s teachings form the foundation of Vedantic thought, inspiring seekers to realize their inner divinity.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/katha-upanishad.jpeg" alt="Katha Upanishad">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Katha Upanishad</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Katha Upanishad</span> presents the dialogue between Nachiketa, a young seeker, and Yama, the Lord of Death, exploring the nature of the soul and the afterlife.</p>
                <p>It delves into deep philosophical themes about self-realization, the imperishable soul (Atman), and the journey towards liberation (Moksha).</p>
                <p>One of its key teachings is that true wisdom transcends material desires and is attained through inner discipline and knowledge.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/mandukya-upanishad.jpeg" alt="Mandukya Upanishad">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Mandukya Upanishad</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Mandukya Upanishad</span> is one of the shortest yet most profound texts, explaining the nature of consciousness through the symbolism of the sacred syllable "Om".</p>
                <p>It describes four states of awareness: waking, dreaming, deep sleep, and the ultimate transcendental state (Turiya).</p>
                <p>This Upanishad is considered a key text for Advaita Vedanta, emphasizing the non-dual nature of existence.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <img src="/images/chadndogya-upanishad.jpeg" alt="Chandogya Upanishad">
            <div class="text">
                <h3>Chandogya Upanishad</h3>
                <p>The <span class="highlight">Chandogya Upanishad</span> is one of the oldest and most comprehensive Upanishads, containing teachings on meditation, ethics, and the unity of the universe.</p>
                <p>It introduces the famous concept of "Tat Tvam Asi" (Thou art That), emphasizing the oneness of the individual soul (Atman) with the Supreme Reality (Brahman).</p>
                <p>This Upanishad elaborates on the importance of inner knowledge, self-discipline, and devotion in realizing ultimate truth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="footer">
            <p>Discover the timeless wisdom of the Vedas and Upanishads and embark on a journey of self-discovery.</p>
